# Project-wide Bazel options for bigquery-emulator.
#
# shellcheck shell=bash  # .bazelrc isn't shell, but editor shellcheck
#                        # integrations sniff it as one. Pin a shell so
#                        # SC2148 ("target shell is unknown") doesn't
#                        # surface against `# Project-wide ...`. bash is
#                        # close enough for the tip lookup; nothing here
#                        # is actually executed.
#
# GoogleSQL is C++20 and ships a hermetic LLVM toolchain through its
# own `MODULE.bazel`, but those toolchain registrations only fire when
# this repo's build is *configured* the same way. Mirror the relevant
# flags from `../googlesql/.bazelrc` here so a top-level
# `bazel build //...` against this repo Just Works.
#
# Clang-specific warning silences (matches `../googlesql/.bazelrc`).
# Without these, the GoogleSQL TU tree raises a wall of warnings the
# upstream tree already suppressed.
build:clang --action_env=BAZEL_CXXOPTS="-std=c++20"
build:clang --cxxopt=-std=c++20
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-module-import-in-extern-c
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-deprecated-declarations
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-range-loop-analysis
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-inconsistent-missing-override
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-char-subscripts
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-enum-compare-switch
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-defaulted-function-deleted
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-unused-private-field
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-return-std-move
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-reorder-ctor
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-unused-const-variable
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-unused-function
build:clang --cxxopt=-Wno-macro-redefined
build:clang --cxxopt=-Werror=undefined-internal

# GCC fallback (kept here for symmetry; the default `--config=clang`
# below means the LLVM toolchain GoogleSQL registers does the work).
build:g++ --action_env=BAZEL_CXXOPTS="-std=c++20"
build:g++ --cxxopt=-std=c++20
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-sign-compare
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-switch
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-unused-function
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-unused-but-set-parameter
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-unused-but-set-variable
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-char-subscripts
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-nonnull-compare
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-return-type
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-class-memaccess
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-deprecated-declarations
build:g++ --cxxopt=-Wno-stringop-truncation

# Default build / test / run options. C++20 is mandatory for GoogleSQL
# (its `<concepts>` usage and the upgrades inside `googlesql/base/`).
# `--java_runtime_version=remotejdk_11` keeps the Java side of the
# GoogleSQL build hermetic so a stray host JDK never sneaks in.
build --cxxopt=-std=c++20 --host_cxxopt=-std=c++20 --config=clang --java_runtime_version=remotejdk_11
test  --cxxopt=-std=c++20 --host_cxxopt=-std=c++20 --config=clang --java_runtime_version=remotejdk_11
run   --cxxopt=-std=c++20 --host_cxxopt=-std=c++20 --config=clang --java_runtime_version=remotejdk_11

# Force Go-built targets to PIE; matches the GoogleSQL .bazelrc note
# about modern Linux toolchains rejecting `R_X86_64_64` relocations
# inside non-PIE objects. Gated behind `--config=googlesql` so the
# flag is only required when a top-level target pulls in
# `@io_bazel_rules_go` transitively through GoogleSQL; pure-C++
# targets in this repo (proto, schema, storage, the in-progress
# Bazel migration of the engine scaffolds) do not need it.
build:googlesql --@io_bazel_rules_go//go/config:linkmode=pie

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# GoogleSQL build-mode selection (Phase 3 of the `googlesql-prebuilt`
# rollout, see `docs/dev/googlesql-prebuilt/README.md`).
#
# The emulator's Bazel build supports two explicit modes for the
# `@googlesql//...` label space:
#
#   --config=googlesql-source    Use a sibling source checkout at
#                                ../googlesql/. This is the DEFAULT
#                                today — `MODULE.bazel`'s
#                                `local_path_override(module_name =
#                                "googlesql", path = "../googlesql")`
#                                already resolves the source tree, so
#                                `--config=googlesql-source` is an
#                                explicit no-op marker that documents
#                                "I deliberately want the source build,
#                                not a prebuilt artifact".
#
#   --config=googlesql-prebuilt  Use the Phase 2 prebuilt artifact.
#                                `--override_module=googlesql=...`
#                                points Bazel's resolver at the
#                                unpacked tarball under
#                                `%workspace%/.cache/googlesql-prebuilt/
#                                googlesql_prebuilt_linux_amd64`. The
#                                cache is populated by
#                                `task googlesql:fetch-prebuilt` (real
#                                published artifact) or
#                                `task googlesql:stage-fixture` /
#                                `task googlesql:stage-bazel` (local
#                                producer runs). Both populate the
#                                cache only after a SHA gate succeeds.
#
# Selection is EXPLICIT. There is no silent fallback: if
# `--config=googlesql-prebuilt` is active and the cache directory does
# not exist (or its `MODULE.bazel` does not declare
# `module(name = "googlesql", ...)`), Bazel refuses to start. Phase 4
# owns flipping defaults, CI lanes, Docker, and release plumbing onto
# `--config=googlesql-prebuilt`; Phase 3 only makes the mode available.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Source mode is a no-op marker today: the repo's `MODULE.bazel`
# already declares the `local_path_override` for `../googlesql`, so
# the existing `task emulator:build-engine:bazel` invocation keeps
# building from source. The marker exists so a caller can write
# `--config=googlesql-source` to make the mode visible in build logs
# / CI configuration.
build:googlesql-source --build_metadata=GOOGLESQL_MODE=source

# Prebuilt mode points the `googlesql` module at the on-disk
# unpacked artifact. The path is `%workspace%`-relative so the same
# config works regardless of where the repo is checked out. The
# cache is populated by `task googlesql:fetch-prebuilt` /
# `task googlesql:stage-bazel` / `task googlesql:stage-fixture`
# (see `taskfiles/googlesql.yml`) — those helpers verify the
# artifact's SHA-256 BEFORE writing into the cache, so a build under
# `--config=googlesql-prebuilt` can trust the cache contents.
build:googlesql-prebuilt --override_module=googlesql=%workspace%/.cache/googlesql-prebuilt/googlesql_prebuilt_linux_amd64
build:googlesql-prebuilt --build_metadata=GOOGLESQL_MODE=prebuilt
# ABI parity with the prebuilt artifact. The Phase 1 manifest commits
# the producer to `-DNDEBUG` (see
# `docs/dev/googlesql-prebuilt/manifest.md`'s `cflags` field), which
# elides `googlesql/public/id_string.h`'s `IdString::CheckAlive() ->
# IdStringPool::CheckPoolIdAlive(...)` debug check from the bundled
# `.pic.o`. The consumer's default `fastbuild` compilation has
# `NDEBUG` UNdefined, so inline `IdString::CheckAlive()` calls expand
# to a reference to `IdStringPool::CheckPoolIdAlive`, which then ends
# up undefined at link time (the bundled archive doesn't have it).
# Forcing `-DNDEBUG` on every TU compiled in prebuilt mode keeps the
# inline expansion in sync. Same principle applies to any other
# `#ifndef NDEBUG`-guarded member function GoogleSQL's headers
# expose for inline use.
#
# This flag flips between modes (source mode keeps the default
# fastbuild ABI). Phase 4 owns standardising the default mode.
build:googlesql-prebuilt --copt=-DNDEBUG
build:googlesql-prebuilt --host_copt=-DNDEBUG

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Local disk cache.
#
# Even with `--config=googlesql-prebuilt` we still compile the full
# Abseil / Protobuf (runtime + protoc) / gRPC / BoringSSL / RE2 / GoogleTest
# trees from source on a cold tree — that's intentional (see
# `docs/dev/googlesql-prebuilt/headers-and-libraries.md` for why those
# third-party deps stay Bzlmod-resolved instead of bundled into
# `libgooglesql.a`). The lever for "don't pay that cost on every cold
# checkout" is Bazel's local disk cache: action outputs land here keyed
# by their action cache hash, so the second build of any of those TUs is
# a cache hit even across `bazel clean` and across fresh worktrees.
#
# Path is workspace-relative on purpose:
#   - Different workspaces / branches may pin different MODULE.bazel
#     versions; sharing a single global cache across workspaces would
#     just create thrash on every dep bump.
#   - `task bazel:cache:clear` should only ever delete THIS workspace's
#     cache, never a sibling clone's.
#   - The `.cache/` prefix matches the existing googlesql-prebuilt cache
#     location (see `.gitignore` and `--config=googlesql-prebuilt`
#     above), so a single `rm -rf .cache/` resets every Bazel-related
#     local cache in one command.
#
# Sizing: a full cold `task emulator:build-engine:bazel` populates
# roughly 6-10 GiB. Bazel does NOT garbage-collect this directory
# automatically (https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/5139); use
# `task bazel:cache:clear` to reclaim space when needed.
#
# Why this is also under `build:` (not `common:`): action-cache hashes
# differ between `bazel build`, `bazel test`, and `bazel coverage` due
# to coverage instrumentation and test runfiles. Sharing a single disk
# cache across all three is correct (Bazel keys by hash), so this lives
# under `build` so the `test`/`run`/`coverage` lines below also inherit
# it via Bazel's flag inheritance.
build --disk_cache=%workspace%/.cache/bazel-disk
test  --disk_cache=%workspace%/.cache/bazel-disk
run   --disk_cache=%workspace%/.cache/bazel-disk
coverage --disk_cache=%workspace%/.cache/bazel-disk

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# First-party C++ warning profile.
#
# `--per_file_copt` lets us turn warnings up only for the trees we own
# without recompiling Abseil / GoogleSQL / DuckDB / gRPC under the
# stricter set. The path regex matches the same first-party roots
# enumerated in `tools/lint/cpp/sources.go::firstPartyIncludeRoots`;
# keep the two in sync when adding a new top-level C++ tree.
#
# Posture (matches `.cursor/plans/cpp_lint_rollout_*.plan.md`):
#
#   - `-Wall -Wextra` are turned on. They are the standard "compile
#     errors waiting to happen" set; clang-18 is the toolchain Bazel
#     pins (see `task emulator:build-engine:bazel`) so the flag set
#     evaluates the same locally and in CI.
#   - `-Werror` is left OFF for now. Once `task lint:cpp:tidy`
#     surfaces and we have triaged the existing warnings, the rollout
#     plan flips this on (and CI gates on it). Until then the slow
#     warnings-only lane catches new code without breaking the cold
#     engine build.
#   - We do NOT add any `-Wno-*` here: warnings GoogleSQL / Abseil
#     emit live in the `--config=clang` flag set above, which only
#     applies to the upstream code that legitimately needs them.
#
# Pattern: `//backend/...:.*` and friends use Bazel's standard label
# regex syntax. The leading `//` anchors the match so a transitively
# included header from a different package does not pick up the
# stricter warnings.
build --per_file_copt=//backend/[/:].*@-Wall,-Wextra
build --per_file_copt=//binaries/[/:].*@-Wall,-Wextra
build --per_file_copt=//frontend/[/:].*@-Wall,-Wextra
build --per_file_copt=//tools/googlesql-prebuilt/smoke/[/:].*@-Wall,-Wextra
